&#xa0;
[normal]1. [bold]About Sightsavers[bold]1.1 
[normal]Sightsavers is an international development organisation which works with partners to eliminate avoidable blindness and promote equality 
[normal]of opportunity for people with disabilities in developing countries. It is estimated that 285 million people across the world are visually impaired, 39 million of which are blind. 80% of global blindness is avoidable, whilst 90% of people who are visually 
[normal]impaired live in developing countries
[normal]. 
[normal]2. [bold]Summary and recommendations[bold]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFID must demonstrate global leadership on this pivotal development issue. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFID need a time-bound, measurable and resourced strategy for disability-inclusive development. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This will r
[normal]equire four important commitments:
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFID should introduce a disability Framework for Results. Starting with a narrow focus on a limited number of countries and sectors will enable DFID to effectively monitor, manage and report progress fro
[normal]m inclusive approaches. It will also enable the collection of disability disaggregated data and allow DFID to assess its impact in improving the lives of people with disabilities. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A coherent strategy outlining this approach will provide a clear path towar
[normal]ds ensuring DFID
[normal]’
[normal]s programmes are inclusive, and therefore more effective.
[normal]3. Introduction[bold]3.1 
[normal]This submission is based on Sightsavers’ experience of working with people with disabilities
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Disability is a crucial but neglected development issue, but there 
[normal]are signs that this situation is beginning to change and the UK should take advantage of this opportunity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This submission addresses all of the questions in the inquiry terms of reference, but focuses on questions 1, 2, 4, 6, 7 and 8 in particular. Further
[normal] information is
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]also supplied in the form of several pieces of supplementary evidence, including a briefing on the ‘We Can Also Make Change’ project the ‘Put Us in the Picture’ report, a case study carried out specifically for this inquiry on the situation
[normal] for disability issues in Uganda, and a research paper on disability and disasters
[normal]. 
[normal]4. [bold]Background: Disability and development[bold]4.1 
[normal]Disability is the outcome of complex interactions between health conditions and the physical and social environment
[normal]. This un
[normal]derstanding of disability is in line with a rights-based approach which emphasises the multitude of barriers people with disabilities face to inclusion in their societies, including in accessing financial services, land ownership, and experiencing stigma a
[normal]nd discrimination. These barriers restrict the power of people with disabilities
[normal] 
[normal]to challenge inequalities and influence their community, reinforcing the relationship between disability and poverty
[normal]. 
[normal]4.2 
[normal]People with disabilities are often reliant on 
[normal]vulnerable livelihoods; face great challenges accessing employment
[normal], adequate health care
[normal] and education
[normal]; have poor access to adequate sanitation and drinking water; are disproportionately affected by hazards; and experience high rates of violence.
[normal](
[normal]Source
[normal]: 
[normal]We Can Also Make Change
[normal])
[normal]4.4 
[normal]The
[normal] rights-based approach is still yet to be fully grasped by many policymakers and governments; therefore much development assistance remains moulded by the inadequate and outdated medical model of disability, which focuses on fixing impairments and providin
[normal]g specialist interventions without addressing the broader societal context of inaccessibility and discrimination. The lack of knowledge amongst policymakers compounds societal barriers and often results in inaccessible poverty-reduction measures, health sy
[normal]stems, physical infrastructure and information materials. 
[normal]4.5 
[normal]Inaccessibility is also influenced by the exclusion of people with disabilities and their organisations from the design, implementation, monitoring and evaluation of development programmes. A 
[normal]lack of engagement is one of four factors identified in a comprehensive literature review
[normal]  which explored the ways people with disabilities are disproportionately affected by environmental hazards (see Annex A). 
[normal]4.6 
[normal]In the last year
[normal],
[normal] progress made at the
[normal] international scale is encouraging. That the High Level Panel Report on the Post 2015 Development Agenda stated “that no person – regardless of ethnicity, gender, geography, disability, race or other status
[normal]” should be left behind is not only welcome but 
[normal]essential. The first ever High Level Meeting on Disability and Development (HLMDD) at the UN General Assembly and its outcome document
[normal] also suggest a significant shift, and that disability is finally being recognised as a development issue by the internat
[normal]ional community. DFID must grasp this historic opportunity to shape an inclusive global agenda. 
[normal]5. [bold]The need for a disability strategy[bold]5.1 
[normal]Through the Disability Knowledge and Research Programmes; the Cross Cutting Disability Research Programmes and suppor
[normal]t for the Disability Rights Fund and internal papers
[normal] 
[normal] DFID has committed to enhancing knowledge of disability. Sightsavers, through the Programme Partnership Agreement grant
[normal], has established an innovation fund to test new and innovative inclusive approa
[normal]ches to meeting the challenges of people with disabilities
[normal].
[normal]5.2 
[normal]Many DFID programmes have an ‘implied inclusion
[normal]’ 
[normal]approach, which assumes programmes that target ‘the most vulnerable
[normal]’ 
[normal]will
[normal] positively impact people 
[normal]with
[normal] 
[normal]disabilities
[normal]. However, as 
[normal]noted at th
[normal]e HLMDD, people with disabilities rarely participate in mainstream programmes
[normal]. Where DFID is funding inclusive approaches, the impact of these programmes is not effectively tracked or measured, making it virtually impossible to assess their impact and bui
[normal]ld an adequate evidence base to inform programme design. 
[normal]5.3 
[normal]We recommend DFID start with 
[normal]a narrow focus on a limited number of countries and sectors. This will enable the collection of disability disaggregated data and allow DFID to assess the effectiveness and cost of inclusive programmes.
[normal]5.4 
[normal]By embedding disability rights into all aspect
[normal]s
[normal] o
[normal]f DFID
[normal]’
[normal]s work; ensuring a real and sustained engagement with people with disabilities; allocating and tracking adequate financial resources; building the capacity of people with disabilities and their organisations; and implementing a robust monitoring and
[normal] evaluation framework, DFID can ensure its work is disability-inclusive. Only through an inclusive approach will DFID
[normal]’
[normal]s work be effective: a framework for results will allow DFID to put into practice inclusive approaches, and measure, manage and report the
[normal]ir impact. 
[normal]5.5 
[normal]DFID must act now, as in September 2014 the UK is required to submit evidence to the Committee on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities
[normal]. The purpose of this is to set out how the rights of people with disabilities are being implemented in accordance with the UNCRPD. 
[normal]Although 
[normal]the UK government’s commitment to the Convention has been strong, the panel will review overall adherence and could
[normal] highlight gaps in evidence and practice on Article 11 – Situations of risk and humanitarian emergencies – and Article 32 – International Cooperation, including inclusive international development programmes
[normal]. A coherent strategy would bring added value to
[normal] meeting the commitments of the UNCRPD by making aid more effective and giving DFID the ability to adequately track progress. 
[normal]6. [bold]Integration of disability issues within DFID’s sector programmes[bold]Health
[normal]6.1 
[normal]Increasingly, evidence is showing that people with
[normal] disabilities experience poorer levels of health than the general population. Whilst some of this is related to increased co-morbidity linked to their impairments, a significant amount of ill health is due to barriers in accessing appropriate information, 
[normal]preventative measures and treatment
[normal]. In health, DFID has a strong commitment to addressing inequity, including providing support in developing strong national health systems that deliver services to the poorest and most marginalised, and its role in helpi
[normal]ng governments progress towards universal health coverage
[normal]. Each year 100 million people are impoverished through health spending
[normal]. While it is not known what proportion of those affected are people with disabilities, the increased costs associated with di
[normal]sability means that people with disabilities are more vulnerable to these financial risks. 
[normal]6.2 
[normal]The UNCRPD requires states to provide equal access to health care and related services for people with disabilities. Article 25 ensures the right of disabled pe
[normal]ople to equally access “the highest attainable standard of health without discrimination on the basis of disability”
[normal]. In DFID priority countries that have ratified the UNCRPD
[normal] 
[normal] DFID can play an important role in improving access to health. 
[normal]6.3 
[normal]DFID also
[normal] recognises the rising prevalence of disability through ageing populations, the rising burden of non-communicable disease and changes in risk patterns to health. What is less clear is what strategic actions DFID are taking to ensure that disability rights 
[normal]are embedded into health programming. 
[normal]6.4 
[normal]DFID should: 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Champion the inclusion of disabled people’s organisations (DPOs) in national health policy and planning
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Facilitate the participation of people with disabilities in programme design, implementation, m
[normal]onitoring and evaluation
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Disaggregate data by disability in all DFID priority programmes to monitor and track progress
[normal]Education
[normal]6.5 
[normal]There is a strong link between disability and marginalisation in education. Despite significant increases in participation 
[normal]over the last decade, and efforts to reduce gender disparities, children with disabilities continue to be left behind. When children with disabilities are excluded from education, their future economic prospects are severely restricted, contributing to a c
[normal]ycle of inter-generational poverty as they establish their own households
[normal]. 
[normal]6.6 
[normal]It is essential that all children, including children with disabilities, are able to access and complete a 
[normal]quality
[normal] basic education delivered through an effective education sys
[normal]tem. 
[normal]Quality
[normal] education requires an inclusive education approach
[normal]; an approach that reduces the stigma and discrimination that contributes to children with disabilities being kept out of school or having a poor quality educational experience. DFID’s announc
[normal]ement in September that it would only build accessible schools is welcome, but to deliver inclusive education, DFID must look beyond physical infrastructure and ensure its education programmes address the wider societal context of inaccessibility and discr
[normal]imination. 
[normal]6.7 
[normal]For all children and adults, opportunities to learn must exist throughout their lives. The global literacy rate for women with disabilities is believed to be as low as 1%
[normal] - therefore DFID must work with governments to promote quality inclu
[normal]sive education and life-long learning. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sightsavers concurs with the Global Campaign for Education’s position that “DFID should develop a high level, cross-cutting strategy on disability, championed at a senior level… complemented by embedding disability-i
[normal]nclusion into core processes, with strong accountability mechanisms to ensure delivery at country level, training and support for all country advisers, and disaggregation of all programmes by disability alongside gender, age and other relevant factors
[normal]”.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFID
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] should also ensure that its education work is not just focused on access but on ensuring that all children, including those with disabilities, benefit from good quality education
[normal]. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFID education programmes should take account of the need for life-lo
[normal]ng learning opportunities, in particular in addressing the low literacy rates among people with disabilities.  
[normal]Water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH)
[normal]6.8 
[normal]DFID’s 2012 Water, Sanitation and Hygiene Portfolio review acknowledged and listed that targeting the p
[normal]oorest will result in more efficient programmes, and lists an increased focus on gender and disability as one of seven guiding principles
[normal]. However, there is no stated framework for implementing and measuring this commitment. DFID also note the impact of p
[normal]oor access on people with physical disabilities
[normal] but lack a clear directive on how to mitigate the barriers to accessing adequate water and sanitation. Through PPAs with organisations such as WaterAid, DFID supports programmes with a strong focus on equity
[normal] and inclusion. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A coherent disability strategy is required in order for DFID to systematically gather data and accurately understand the reach and impact of it water, sanitation and hygiene programmes on people with disabilities. 
[normal]              
[normal]7. [bold]The strength of the [bold]evidence base on what works: inclusive approaches[bold]7.1 
[normal]Sightsavers has been developing its evidence base through a collaborative participatory research project
[normal]. Findings from Bangladesh demonstrate the value of a participatory approach in building knowledge and identifying priority areas of disability issues. 
[normal](Source: We Can Also Make Change
[normal])
[normal]7.3 
[normal]Engagement with the poorest and most margi
[normal]nalised groups is essential in order to inform effective policies. It ensures agencies do not form inaccessible or discriminatory programmes and that they account for the diversity of disability rather than apply an ineffective generic approach
[normal]. Engagemen
[normal]t is at the heart of the twin-track approach, which remains the most effective way of implementing inclusive programmes. This involves mainstreaming an inclusive approach into all development programmes, whilst referring to specialist organisations where n
[normal]ecessary; and working with people with disabilities and their organisations to build their capacity to advocate for their rights and inclusive approaches
[normal].
[normal]7.4 
[normal]Central to the twin-track approach is the importance of advocating with and building the 
[normal]capacity of people with disabilities and their organisations to access their rights. One example of advocacy and capacity building is demonstrated in a disability-inclusive disaster management and sustainable livelihoods programme in Bangladesh (see Annex 
[normal]B), funded by DFID through the Sightsavers Innovation Fund
[normal]. 
[normal]7.5 
[normal]Despite being an early advocate of the twin-track approach
[normal] DFID have failed to demonstrate systematically inclusive approaches. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A coherent disability strategy, applying the best practice o
[normal]f the twin-track approach, will enable DFID to implement more inclusive – and effective – programmes.  
[normal]8. [bold]Financial costs and benefits: Accessible costs [bold]8.1 
[normal]In order to ensure inclusive approaches, accessibility costs must be considered at all stages of 
[normal]the project cycle. Adequately budgeting for these costs is essential and will allow DFID to allocate and track adequate financial resources
[normal]. DFID must be realistic about the resources that are required. However, accessibility costs should not be viewed as
[normal] additional; they are a necessary requirement of effective development assistance. 
[normal]8.2 
[normal]Perceptions
[normal] of accessibility costs as expensive additions to programme budgets not only neglect the rights of people with disabilities, but also fail to recognise the p
[normal]otential economic benefits of inclusive policies. An International Labour Organisation study found that 10 low- and middle- income countries were losing between 3 and 7% of GDP through the exclusion of people with disabilities from the labour market. The f
[normal]igures below estimate the ‘price of exclusion
[normal]’ 
[normal]identified in the report for six DFID priority countries
[normal].  These demonstrate the severity of economic exclusion in real terms, whilst highlighting the economic benefits removing barriers to participation of p
[normal]eople with disabilities in labour markets could bring. 
[normal]8.3 [bold]Estimated economic losses related to disability for six DFID priority countries[bold]Country[bold]Economic losses[bold]Total US$ (Millions)[bold]% GDP (2006 GDP figures)[bold]Ethiopia
[normal]667
[normal]5.01
[normal]Malawi
[normal]99
[normal]3.12
[normal]South 
[normal]Africa
