[normal]3.75
[normal]&#xa0;[bold](Source: The Price of Exclusion: The economic consequences of excluding people with disabilities from the world of work
[normal])
[normal]8.4 
[normal]The cost of exclusion comes at a heavy price for many 
[normal]countries, but the challenge of adequately allocating accessibility costs is underlined by the lack of accurate data on disability and the costs of inclusive approaches
[normal]. The case of Uganda (see Annex C) outlines these challenges, and also shows how, after
[normal] advocating with partners, the 2014 national census will include questions on disability
[normal]. This demonstrates the results that can be gained through concerted advocacy efforts. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFID should adequately budget for accessibility costs in all programmes 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9. [bold]Ma[bold]instreaming and training[bold]9.1 
[normal]In line with Article 32 of the UNCRPD, DFID must ensure its development assistance is inclusive. This can be achieved by mainstreaming a disability perspective and providing sensitisation training
[normal] – on a level with recent gend
[normal]er initiatives – to all staff, and specialist training on inclusive approaches to specific departments where required – for example, training humanitarian staff on disability-inclusive disaster risk reduction methods. In addition to identifying senior foca
[normal]l points responsible for strategy implementation, DFID must ensure inclusive approaches are embedded within the role of Social Development Advisors by providing specialist training so that they are adequately equipped to provide support on inclusive approa
[normal]ches. This should include knowledge of the disability sector and key organisations for referral in DFID priority countries, in line with the twin-track approach. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Through the implementation of a coherent disability strategy, DFID should embed disability ri
[normal]ghts into all aspects of its work.
[normal]10. [bold]The role of the UK: Working with partners and influencing the post-2015 framework[bold]10.1 
[normal]DFID should promote inclusive approaches as a human rights issue to partners of all levels; from communities to NGOs and governmen
[normal]ts. Many efforts to build capacity have rightly focused on people with disabilities and their organisations, but DFID must also support governments to promote and implement inclusive approaches
[normal]. The mandate of the Convention also gives DFID space to use a
[normal] range of aid modalities – including bilateral, multi-lateral, civil and private sector support – to support governments and place inclusive conditions as part of their agreements to ensure adequate levels of inclusion are met. The potential of inclusive d
[normal]onor funding is demonstrated in Uganda, where a barrier to inclusive approaches is not the existence of national policies but their implementation. In 2009 DFID commissioned a scoping study of disability including recommendations outlining how DFID could s
[normal]upport inclusive policies
[normal]. However, DFID has not followed up these recommendations, so their development assistance in Uganda has not had the catalytic impact it could have had. 
[normal]10.2 
[normal]Sightsavers commends DFID for its prominent role in ensuring the High L
[normal]evel Panel report called for the post-2015 framework to be inclusive. However, this is not legally binding, and there remains much work to do. The Millennium Development Goals did not explicitly mention disability
[normal] at all. This resulted in inclusive approaches not being prioritised by developing country governments, and also meant that donors such as DFID, that rigorously applied the MDG agenda, supported programmes that were not inclusive. In the case of health, as
[normal] a direct consequence, persons with disabilities have been excluded from national plans and until recently were not systematically present in DFID’s own business cases and country operational plans
[normal]. The recent inclusivity requirement in all business cases
[normal] is significant and welcomed. 
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We urge DFID to build on this progress by creating a coherent strategy, and to use its political capital to influence other nations on the importance of a disability-inclusive post-2015 framework to ensure development goals n
[normal]ever again exclude people with disabilities and other marginalised groups. 
